{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_amaryllis_ver01/data/sn83007243/00414210247/1957083001/0089.xml":{"full_text":"It Spiritual Maanir$\nof Labor Day\n7ir *-Jwt A Fare*?\n.t Page Pour\nVol. VI, No. 48\nEnrollment\n\"Again Sets\n28,000 Students Return\nTo Classes in Diocese\nAn increase of more than a thousand students is ex\nfleeted to swell the Diocesan School enrollment when the\nmajority of the local schools open their doors next week,\naccording to Monsignor Bennett C. Applegate, superin\ntendent of Diocesan schools.\nSome 28,000 students will be\ngin classes next Wednesday and\nThursday, September 3-4, Mon\nsignor Applegate said.\nElementary schools will begin\nclasses on Wednesday' with most\nof the high schools opening their\ndoors on Thursday.\nAn exception will be the new\nBishop Hartley High School,\nLivingston Ave. and Zettler Rd.,\nwhich will begin classes on\nWednesday, Sept, 11, at 9:30\na.m. for the seventh and eighth\ngrade students enrolled there,\nwith the ninth grade or fresh\nman class reporting the follow\ning day September 12, also at\n9:30 a.m.\nThis delay is necessary in order\nto ready the recently finished\nclassrooms according to Monsig\nnor Edward Spiers, acting princi\npal of Hartley.\nTen new principals will greet\npupils in Diocesan schools next\nweek, according to a report is\nsued from the school office this\nweek.\nIn Columbus t+ie new high\nschool principals are: Sr. M.\nEdwin, Holy Family Sr. Mary\nOur Schools ^Are Not Churches\nMonsignor Paul O'Dea prefect of studies at St. Charles,\nfreaking at the Mass in St. Joseph Cathedral attended\nby more than seven hundred lay*\nand religious teachers, said that\nthe greatest danger to our educa\ntional system is not in those who\nwould undermine it but to \"con\ndemn by association those who\nvouch for our right to exist and\nconduct schools.\"\n\"We can lose many sincere\n.friends,\" he said, \"and honest\nHfrpporters when we attribute\nto them the statements of a few\nprofessional educators or indi\nviduals or groups in a com\nmunity.\"\nMonsignor O'Dea reminded the\nlocal educators that the American\nsystem of education is composed\nof three types of schools, namely,\ntax-supported, religious, and pri\nvate.\n\"Our bishops have constantly\njuaintained,\" he said, \"that the\nCatholic Church is not opposed\nto tax-supported srhools. On the\ncontrary, she heartily endorses\nour system of compulsory educa\ntion in America she sincerely\ncommends the traditional freedom\n0* American education.\n\"She knows,\" he continued,\n\"that her own schools are ren\ndering an unsurpassed public\nfUrvice. She knows her schools\n,^Pe schools not churches.\nThe Catholic school is not\nfjWASHINGTON \u2014(NC)\nCatholic schools again will\nset a new enrollment record\nthis September if expansion\ncontinues and there's\nlittle room for doubt considering\n&e past 15 year's growth.\nElementary schools this fall\nwill register about 3,880,000 pu\npils for an estimated increase of\nabout 95,000 over last fall.\n^High schools will enroll this\nSeptember an estimated 760,000\nstudents, accounting for an in\ncrease of about 10,000 over last\nfall.\nThe combined total for thess\nJfco levels of Catholic education\nJAould be about 4,640,000, an\naitimate by the N.C.W.C. News\nService reveals. Official stud*\nies will be available at the end\n\u2022f the school year. The news\nService estimate is intended\n\u2022etily as a general indication of\nenrollment.\no e e s a n u n i v e s i i e s\nshould be nudging the 315.000\nmark this fall, for an increase of\nv\n-m\n1\nJ\"\ni\n1\nVSF-\n'i\nAquinas, S.C.N., Ouf Lady of\nVictory, who will also head the\nelementary departments, and\nSister Sharon, O.S.P., Sacred\nHeart.\nSister M. Francis da Sales,\nO.P., will head both the high\nand grade school at St. Francis\nda Sales, Newark.\nNew principals in tha Colum\nbus elementary schools are: Sr.\nM. Caroline, S.N.D., St. Joseph's\nCathedral, Sr. M. Josine, O.S.F.,\nCorpus Christi, Sr. Francis\nClare, O.P., Holy Spirit Mother\nBernadine, O.S.F., St. John\nthe Evangelist and Sr. M. Ter\n\u2022nee, O.S.F., St. Mary Magda*\nlane.\nSister Helen Francis, S.N.D.,\nwill head St. John's alaman\ntary school, Logan.\nAssisting Monsignor Apple\ngate in the administration of the\nDiocesan School office are: Sis\nters M. Gregory, high school\nsupervisor and Sisters M. Da\nChantal, O.S.F., end Sister M.\nCharlene, elementary supervis\nors.\nMonsignor O'Dea Asks\nMutual Understanding\nOf School Systems\nA plea for mutual understanding of the three schoo_\nsystems in the United States was made last Wednesday at\nthe opening of the fifty-fifth Diocesan teachers' meeting.\nfailing to do anything that any\nstandardized American school\nshould do. As evidence of this,\nwe have only to look to the\nthem# of this year's education\nmeeting, \"The State School\nStandards and the Catholic Cur\nriculum.\"\nMonsignor O'Dea said that we\nshould not be fearful when our\nschool system is attacked. \"In\ntheir anxiety to make a monolith\nof education, some educators de\ncry the fact that many children\nare denied the solid experience\nof a common school system. They\nsay a separate school system is di\nvisive and would scare an other\nwise united people.\n\"Other critics propound,\" he\ncontinued, \"that religion has no\nplace in a school it is the provid\nence of the home not the school\nto bring forth religious instruc\ntion. Sectarian animosities have\ngrown all too frequent in the con\ndemnation and harassment of the\nparochial school system.\n\"Finally,\" he said, \"there is that\ngroup of wilfull and energetic\nmen who reject religion in all\nforms and activities as a funda\nmental position.\"\nCommenting on the admiration\n(Continued on Page 2)\nCatholic School Enrollment\nUp 100,000 Across the Nation\nabout 5,000 students, it indi\ncated in the estimate.\nBoth grade schools and high\nschools will double their enroll\nment in a 15 year- period, 1945\nIB60, if the projection made last\nApril by the NCWC Department\nol Education holds true.\nBy 1960, said the projection,\ngrade schools should be enroll*\ning more than 4.3 million stu\ndents, representing a 100 per\ncent increase ovor their 1945\nenrollment total o* about 2,086*\n794. They went over three mil\nlion for the first time in Oc\ntober, 1954.\nThat same year, high schools\nmay register more than 900,000\nstudents, thus doubling the total\nfrom the 1945 figure of 420,000,\nthe projection indicated.\nThe news service estimate did\nnot include a tally of new teach,\ners or buildings this fall. But last\nApril's NCWC Education Depart\nment estimate said that for the\n1956-57 school year, there were\nP.700 grade schools staffed b^\nA *T1ff\nNEWSPAPER 0IVI310*\nOHIO STATS ff'JSRUi\nlOLUMB'JS 1 0 i i\nNew Hartley\nSchool Open$ v\nWeek Late\nSister Ludlfe, S.N.&,\nassistant principal at the\nnew Hartlay High School,\nLivingston Avenue and\nZattler Road, greets e\nprospective student, one\nof th# more than 28,000\nin the Diocese who will\nbegin classes during the\nnext two weeks. Bishop\nHartley High School will\nnot begin classes until Sep\ntember 11 when the sev\nenth and eighth grade\nstudents will report. The\nFreshman class will re\nport the following day.\nMore time was needed to\nready the newly finished\nclassrooms. Below, some\nof the teaching Sisters of\nNotre Dame, who will\nstaff the new Hartley High\nSchool straighten the Li\nbrary.\n,1U ter. it\n4W*\nJJ*S\n,'i\nJ-\nt*\ni\nu\ni.\n'I\n89,000 teachers and 2,350 high\nschools staffed by 35,000 instruc\ntors.\nEnrollment expansion in all\nschools, Catholic and other, is\nreflected in a report issued this\nmonth by U.S. Education Com\nmissioner Lawrence G. Der\nthick.\nPlacing the total attendance at\nschools of all types at 43,135,000,\nMr. Derthick's report said this\nmeant one of every four persons\nin the United States will be in\nschool. He estimated this fall's\ntotal enrollment as about 1,769,\n000 above that of last .year..\nAbout 26,037,000 pupils will\nbe in public grade schools this\nyear as against 25,283,00 last\nyear, said Mr. Derthick. An es\ntimated 7,399,000 will be at\ntending public high schools as\ncompared to about 6,876/000\nlast yoar, he declared.\nThe commissioner's report put\nthe number of students at univer\nsities, colleges and professional\n(Continued on Page 2)\nv 1\n7\nvr-.r\nA j*-* v~\nv\n4\nColumbus 16, Ohio, Friday, August 30, 1957\nCincinnati\nTo Host 1958\nliturgy Week\nCOLLEGEVILLE, Minn.\u2014(NC)\n\u2014Archbishop Karl J. Alter of\nCincinnati will be host to next\nyear's North American Liturgical\nConference, the conference board\nof directors announced here.\nThe announcement came at the\nconclusion of the 12th liturgical\nweek held here at St. John's Ben\nedictine Abbey to discuss ways of\nincreasing understanding of the\nform and content of the Church's\npublic services of worship.\nFather Shawn Sheehan, St.\nJohn's Seminary, Brighton, Mass.,\nwas re-elected president of the\nliturgical conference. Other offi\ncers are: Father Alphonse E.\nWesthoff, St. Peter's Church,\nKirkwood,' Mo., vice-president\nFather Aloysius F. Wilmes, Sa\ncred Heart Church, Elsberry, M0.,\nsecretary, and Father Norbert E.\nRandolph, Chicago, treasurer.\nAnother announcement by the\nconference board of directors\nsaid plans are being made for the\nestablishment of a permanent of\nfice with a full-time staff mem\nber.\n\u20223B\nrj\ni\nSt. James\nChapel\nMsgr. Ptfwird 5|#Nfrs,\nacting principal of Hart\nley, stands at the doorway\nof St. James Chapel,\nwhere students will have\nan opportunity to assist\nat Mass and make visits to\nthe Blessed Sacrament.\nBelow the beautiful inter\nior of the chapel, the wing\non the left separated by\ngrill work is for the teach\ning nuns who will be in\nresidence at the school.\nThe school is named in\nhonor of the Fourth Bish\nop of Columbus, James J.\nHartley.\nHungarians\nPack Churches\nIn Protest\nVIENNA\u2014(NC)\u2014As Hungary'\nRed regime continues its new\nwave of terrorism against the\nChurch, that nation's Catholics\nprotested by flocking in greater\nnumbers than ever to Budapest\nchurches to mark the feast of\ntheir patron St. Stephen.\nAccording to reports reaching\nhere, the huge Esztergom basicila\nand all Budapest churches were\nfilled to overflowing on August\n20, the day St. Stephen's feast is\ncelebrated in Hungary. It is ob\nserved elsewhere on September 2\nThe turnout is interpreted\nhere as a sign of popular reac\ntion against th\u00bb recent execa\ntion of Father Laszlo Minds\nzenti, who was accused of aid\ning freedom fighters during last\nfall's anti-communist uprising.\nMeanwhile, with 500 priests al\nready in prison, arrests continue\nLatest act of persecution, reports\nstate, is the jailing of all mem\nbers of the senior class of the\nBudapest Central Theological\nSeminary.\n(Continued on Page 2)\nParish, Cell\nOf Mystical'\nBody\u2014Pope\nCASTELGANDOLFO, Italy\nThe parish is a cell of the Mys\ntical Body of Christ, His Holiness\nPope Pius XII told a parish pil\ngrimage from Barcelona, Spain,\nurinf! an audience here.\nShaking 'o the pastor and\n(.arishioners of San Medin par\n**h, the Pop* said: 'To tell you\nto love your parish is unreces\nsary since it would be like tell\ning you to love yourselves.\"\nHe exhorted them not to cease\ntheir efforts to improve parish\nlife until they have turned it into\nmodel \"in which there is no\nmemjer spiritually sick or separ\nated and in which an authentic\nChristian life is lived.\"\n\"Authentic Christian life,\" he\nsaid, is manifest in love, in\nprayer, in respect for sacrifice,\nin purity of youth, in sound\nmorals by adults, in regular\nattendance at divine services\nand frequent reception of the\nsacraments.\nIt further is manifest by gen\nerous charity to the needy and by\nexact fulfillment of all civic du\nties, the Pope said.\nThe pilgrimage was composed\nof 450 members of the parish.\nSan Medin in Barcelona is in a\nworkers' district and has, since\nits foundation in 1947. been out\nstanding in its religious and social\nlife.\n'Are You Active?9\nFour practices to fulfill this\nresponsiblity are recommended in\nthe statement released here by\nMsgr. George G. Higgins. director\nof the department. The four\npoints are:\n\u2014Individual trade unionists\nare required to attend and par\nticipate intelligently and vocal*\nly in local and regional union\nmeetings\n\u2014Members should be willing\nto serve as committee mem\nbers and officers of unions,\n\"even at the cost of personal\ninconvenience\n\u2014The rank-and-file should\nproceed on thjir own initiative\nto eliminate abuses at the local\nunion level, and\n\u2014Individual members have\nan obligation to solve the labor\nracketeering problem on their\nown initiative at the local level.\nA prediction that the current\ninvestigations into labor rack\neteering bv a Senate Select Com\nmittee \"will ultimately prove to\nhave been extremely beneficial\nto the labor movement and, in\ndirectly, to the cause of collective\nbargaining\" is made in the begin\nning of the statement.\n\"There is no immediate reason\nto fear,\" the message sayr, \"that\nthe sins of an unfaithful minority\noi racketeers will be visited on\nthe majority of honest and truly\ndedicated labor leaders.\"\nThe statement takes favorable\nnote of \"the wholehearted co\noperation\" given to the investi\ngations by the AFL-CIO and also\nof the \"fair and objective man\nner\" in which the committee\nheaded by John J. McClellan\nof Arkansas has conducted the\nprobe.\nBy Jim Shoa\nCINCINNATI (NO\nParents who coddle their\nchildren may be undermin\ning the youngster's mental\nhealth, according to a Jesuit\npriest who is a national leader in\nthe Recovery, Inc., movement for\npersons who have been afflicted\nnervous and mental ailments.\nJesuit Father John J. Higgins,\none-time victim of a mental ail\nment, told an interviewer-:\n\"Poor disciplinary training\nof children is a major factor in\nthe nation's number one health\nproblem menta' illness.\"\nHe cited recent official figures\nshowing that approximately 10\nmillion Americans suffer some\nform of mental illness, and that\n\"every other hospital bed in the\nU.S.\" is allotted to a mental case.\nFather Higgins. who teaches\nphilosophy, psychology and edu\ncation at Parks College, aero\nnautical section of St. Louis (Mo.)\nUniversity, and who is a licensed\nairplane pilot, declared:\n\"Many of today's children are\nLong Active in Industrial\nDevelopment, Arbitration\nFather Cornelius Gallagher, who has been actfve in\nthe field of industrial relations for many ears, will be the\npreacher for the thirteenth annual Labor Day Ma.cs at 9\na.m. in St. Joseph Cathedral.\nBishop Edward G. Hettinger, administrator of the\nDiocese will be celebrant for the\nMass which annually fills the Ca\nthedral with men from the ranks\nof management and labor.\nCORRECTION\nThe annual labor day\nMass has been changad\nto 9 a.m. as reported in\ntoday's story.\nAssisting Bishop Hettinger will\nbe Father Thomas Cadden, as\nsistant pastor St. Catharine par\nish, deacon, and Fr. John Tague,\nEvery Union Member\nResponsible for Ethics\nAnnual Message Says\nWASHINGTON Rank and file members of unions\nhave the primary responsibility\u2014a religious responsibility\n\u2014for maintaining high ethical standards in the labor move\nment, accordng to the 1957 Labor Day Statement of the\nSocial Action Department of the National Catholic Welfare\nConference.\nThough the Codes of Ethical\nPractices adopted by the AFL-.\nCIO to assure a spotless labor\nmovement earn the statement's\n\"highest praise,\" the effect of\nthese is overshadowed by the re\nsponsibility of individuals in the\nunions, according to the message.\n\"Responsibility for maintain\ning high ethical standards in the\nlabor movement rests squarely, as\na matter of conscience, on the\nmillions of individual men and\nwomen who comprise the mem\nbership of the organizations affil\niated with the parent federation,\nit maintains, adding that the prob.\nlem of apathy or indifference is a\nreligious one.\n\"The only effective remedy is\na genuine religious and moral re\nvival in the best sense of the\nword\u2014a profound renewal of the\nChristian spirit based on the pre\nserving practice of prayer and\npenance and a thorough training\nin the essentials of Christian so\ncial teaching,\" the statement says.\nDCCW Board\nGets Two New\nMember*\nTwo new appointments to the\nBoard of Directors of the Colum\nbus Diocesan Council of Catho\nlie Women have been made by\nMrs. Leo H. Jennings, diocesan\npresident.\nMrs. Chester Croce, St. James\nthe Less Parish, has assumed the\nchairmanship of the Committee\non Parent Teacher Associations\nand Mrs. William F. Langlev, St\nAndrew's Parish, will serve as-the\nCouncil's parliamentarian.\nChild Coddling May Undermine\nTheir Mental Health, Priest Says\nbrought up in such an atmos\nphere of comfort-worship that\nthey are not equipped to handle\nthe discomforts and setbacks that\nare inevitable.\"\nThe genial, white-haired Jesuit\ndcesn't believe in \"old-fashioned,\nbig stick discipline.\"\n\"But the youngsters should\nbe taught in the family to ac\ncept the responsibility of per\nforming definite chores, of\nhelping with the housework, of\nstudying their lessons, and do\ning their homework.\"\nInstead, he said, many of them\nare plagued with \"a controlling\ndesire for an excessive amount of\nentertainment, and they stay out\nevery night to all hours.\"\nCorrectly motivated discipline\nwill bring the children to adopt\na \"mature, reasonable, common\nsense attitude toward growing up\nand accepting responsibility,\" Fa\nther Higgins declared.\n\"Paramount in pro v i i n\nchildren with adequate disci\npline,\" he added, \"is the exam\nple of the parents. Unreason\u00ad\nv -'.v\nMovitt\nRatad\nOn Page Twe\nPrice Tan Cants $3.00 A Yaar\nFr. Gallagher\nLabor Day\nSpeaker Here\nassistant pastor Our Lady of\nPeace parish, sub-deacon.\nDeacons of Honor to the Bishop\nwill be Monsignors Bennett Ap\nplegate and Lawrence Corcoran.\nAssistant priest will be Fr. Au\ngustine Winkler, diocesan direc\ntor of social action.\nMonsignor James J. Carroll will\nbe master of ceremonies.\nFather Gallagher, who is now\npastor of ASumption parish,\nbarnesviUe, in the Diocese of\nSteubenville, has been prominent\nin promoting industrial develop\nment in areas which were losing\npopulation due to lack of eco\nnomic resources.\nHe has been responsible for\nthe return and the relocation of\nindustry to the BarnesviUe ai a.\nFather Gallagher, who is a for\nmer director of Social Action for\nthe Steubenville Diocese, is also\nr.ctive in labor-management rela\ntions having served as a member\nof the American Arbitration Serv\nice which is a service organization\nfurnishing arbitrators in labor\nmanagement bargaining talks.\nEveryone in the Diocese is urg\ned to assist at the annual Labor\nDay Mass according to Fr. Augus\ntine Winkler, diocesan director\nof Social Action.\nMiss Lowry\nTo Arrange\nDCCW Meet\nAntoinette Lowry,\nI\n'4? \"'^if\nsr\nHoly\nNama\nparish, has been named general\nchairman of the Twelfth Annual\nConvention of the Columbus Dio\ncesan Council of Catholic Women\nto be held on Oct. 26 and 27 at\nthe Deshler-Hilton Hotel.\nMiss Lowry is currently serv\ning as vice-president of the Cen-\nMiss Lowry\ntral Deanery DCCW and is past\npresident of the Holy Name\nPCCW, the Catholic Women's\nLeague, and the Guilds of St. Ra\nphael Home for the Aged.\nA teacher in the Bexley Pub\n(Continued on page 3)\nable behavior by the parent*\u2014\narguing, bickering, excessive\ndrinking, and so on\u2014leads to a\nbreakdown of the children's be\nhavior.\"\nHe summed up by observing\nthat \"in the 20th century the\nfamily has lost the art of living\nand playing together,\" and for\nthis reason the family also has\n\"lost the art of learning self*\ndiscipline from those nearest aud\ndearest to them.\nRecovery, Inc. groups have\nproved a valuable factor in\nproviding victims of mental\nand nervous ailments with an\nopportunity to help each other\nachieve mental health through\nwill training, Father Higgins\nsaid.\nFirst organized 20 years ago\nat Chicago by the late Dr. Abra*\nham Low, who outlined the tech\nniques of recovery groups an\u00abl\nwrote recovery's textbook, \"Men*\ntal Health Through Will-Train*\ning,\" recovery now-has more thai!\n225 groups active in 25 states.\n(Continued on Page 2)\nk\"\nv","height":"27138","width":"19449"}}
